          "body": "The chapter's central argument: the very existence of Psalm 110:4 in Israel's scripture proves the Levitical priesthood was always intended to be superseded. If perfection (*teleiōsis*) had come through the Levitical priesthood, why would God Himself, centuries after Sinai, swear to David's Lord that he would be a priest *according to a different order*? The Levitical priesthood and its accompanying Mosaic law are structurally fused (7:12) — change one, change the other. Jesus, from Judah, could not officiate at the earthly altar (7:13-14); His priesthood operates not on \"a law of physical requirement\" (genealogical descent from Aaron) but on \"the power of an indestructible life\" (7:16). The former commandment is *set aside* (athetēsis, 7:18) because it was weak and useless — not because it was evil but because it could not deliver what it promised."
